      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">US vs UK Pint: Why They Are Different Sizes</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 28, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>Order a pint of beer in London and you get more than in New York. Despite sharing the same name, a US pint and a UK (imperial) pint are different volumes. Here is why and how much the difference actually matters.</p>

      <h2>The Numbers</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">US pint = 473 mL (16 US fl oz)</p>
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400 mt-1">UK pint = 568 mL (20 UK fl oz)</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">A UK pint is 20% larger than a US pint</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Why Are They Different?</h2>
      <p>Both countries once used the same English wine gallon (defined in 1707). But they diverged:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>1707:</strong> The English wine gallon (231 cubic inches) was standardised — the US kept this</li>
        <li><strong>1824:</strong> Britain redefined the gallon as the volume of 10 pounds of water at 62°F (the imperial gallon = 277.4 cubic inches)</li>
        <li><strong>Result:</strong> The US gallon (3,785 mL) is smaller than the imperial gallon (4,546 mL)</li>
        <li>Since a pint is 1/8 of a gallon in both systems, the pint sizes diverged too</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Fluid Ounce Confusion</h2>
      <p>To add to the confusion, even fluid ounces differ:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>1 US fluid ounce = 29.57 mL</li>
        <li>1 UK fluid ounce = 28.41 mL</li>
        <li>A US pint = 16 US fl oz = 473 mL</li>
        <li>A UK pint = 20 UK fl oz = 568 mL</li>
      </ul>
      <p>So while the UK fluid ounce is slightly smaller, there are more of them in a pint, making the UK pint significantly larger overall.</p>

      <h2>Practical Impact</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Beer:</strong> A "pint" in the UK gives you 95 mL more beer than in the US</li>
        <li><strong>Recipes:</strong> A recipe from a British cookbook calling for "1 pint of stock" means 568 mL, not 473 mL</li>
        <li><strong>Milk:</strong> A UK "pint of milk" is 568 mL; US milk is sold by the quart (946 mL) or gallon</li>
        <li><strong>Legal measures:</strong> UK pubs must serve beer in certified imperial pint glasses (marked with a crown)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Other Countries</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Australia:</strong> Uses metric — a "pint" at a pub is 570 mL (imperial) or sometimes 425 mL (a "schooner")</li>
        <li><strong>Ireland:</strong> Uses the imperial pint (568 mL)</li>
        <li><strong>Canada:</strong> Officially metric but uses imperial pints for draught beer</li>
        <li><strong>Continental Europe:</strong> Beer comes in metric measures (250 mL, 330 mL, 500 mL)</li>
      </ul>

